# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: haxe-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript is used primarily for the development of websites and software targeting the Adobe Flash platform, originally finding use on web pages in the form of embedded SWF files.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript 3 is also used with the Adobe AIR system for the development of desktop and mobile applications.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] The language itself is open-source in that its specification is offered free of charge and both an open-source compiler (as part of Apache Flex) and open-source virtual machine (Tamarin) are available.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript was also used with Scaleform GFx for the development of three-dimensional video-game user interfaces and heads up displays.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript was initially designed for controlling simple two-dimensional vector animations made in Adobe Flash (formerly Macromedia Flash).
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Initially focused on animation, early versions of Flash content offered few interactivity features, thus had very limited scripting ability.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Later versions added functionality allowing for the creation of web-based games and rich web applications with streaming media (such as video and audio).
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Today, ActionScript is suitable for desktop and mobile development through Adobe AIR; it is used in some database applications and in basic robotics as in Make Controller Kit.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Flash MX 2004 introduced ActionScript 2.0, a scripting language more suited to the development of Flash applications.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Saving time is often possible by scripting something rather than animating it, which usually also enables a higher level of flexibility when editing.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Since the arrival of the Flash Player 9 alpha (in 2006), a newer version of ActionScript has been released, ActionScript 3.0.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] This version of the language is intended to be compiled and run on a version of the Tamarin virtual machine, formerly ActionScript Virtual Machine 2, that was also fully rewritten (dubbed AVM2).
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Because of this, code written in ActionScript 3.0 is generally targeted for Flash Player 9 and higher, and will not work in prior versions.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] At the same time, ActionScript 3.0 executes up to 10 times faster than legacy ActionScript code due to the just-in-time compiler enhancements.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Flash libraries can be used with the XML abilities of the browser to render rich content in the browser.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] This technology is known as Asynchronous Flash and XML, much like AJAX.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Adobe offers its Flex product line to meet the demand for rich web applications built on the Flash runtime, with behaviors and programming done in ActionScript.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript 3.0 forms the foundation of the Flex 2 application programming interface (API).
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript started as an object-oriented programming language for Macromedia's Flash authoring tool, later developed by Adobe Systems as Adobe Flash.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] The first three versions of the Flash authoring tool provided limited interactivity features.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Early Flash developers could attach a simple command, called an "action", to a button or a frame.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] The set of actions was basic navigation controls, with commands such as "play", "stop", "getURL", and "gotoAndPlay".
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] With the release of Flash 4 in 1999, this simple set of actions became a small scripting language.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] New capabilities introduced for Flash 4 included variables, expressions, operators, if statements, and loops.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Although referred to internally as "ActionScript", the Flash 4 user manual and marketing documents continued to use the term "actions" to describe this set of commands.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] With the release of Flash 5 in September 2000, the "actions" from Flash 4 were enhanced once more and named "ActionScript" for the first time.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] This was the first version of ActionScript with influences from JavaScript and the ECMA-262 (Third Edition) standard, supporting the said standard's object model and many of its core data types.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Local variables may be declared with the var statement, and user-defined functions with parameter passing and return values can also be created.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Notably, ActionScript could now also be typed with a text editor rather than being assembled by choosing actions from drop-down lists and dialog box controls.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Two important features of ActionScript that distinguish it from later versions are its loose type system and its reliance on prototype-based inheritance.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Loose typing refers to the ability of a variable to hold any type of data.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] This allows for rapid script development and is particularly well-suited for small-scale scripting projects.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Prototype-based inheritance is the ActionScript 1.0 mechanism for code reuse and object-oriented programming.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Instead of a class keyword that defines common characteristics of a class, ActionScript 1.0 uses a special object that serves as a "prototype" for a class of objects.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] All common characteristics of a class are defined in the class's prototype object and every instance of that class contains a link to that prototype object.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] The next major revision of the language, ActionScript 2.0, was introduced in September 2003 with the release of Flash MX 2004 and its corresponding player, Flash Player 7.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] In response to user demand for a language better equipped for larger and more complex applications, ActionScript 2.0 featured compile-time type checking and class-based syntax, such as the keywords class and extends.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] While this allowed for a more structured object-oriented programming approach, the code would still be compiled to ActionScript 1.0 bytecode, allowing it to be used on the preceding Flash Player 6 as well.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] In other words, the class-based inheritance syntax was a layer on top of the existing prototype-based system.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] With ActionScript 2.0, developers could constrain variables to a specific type by adding a type annotation so that type mismatch errors could be found at compile-time.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript 2.0 also introduced class-based inheritance syntax so that developers could create classes and interfaces, much as they would in class-based languages such as Java and C++.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] This version conformed partially to the ECMAScript Fourth Edition draft specification.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] In June 2006, ActionScript 3.0 debuted with Adobe Flex 2.0 and its corresponding player, Flash Player 9.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript 3.0 was a fundamental restructuring of the language, so much so that it uses an entirely different virtual machine.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Flash Player 9 contains two virtual machines, AVM1 for code written in ActionScript 1.0 and 2.0, and AVM2 for content written in ActionScript 3.0.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript 3.0 added limited support for hardware acceleration (DirectX, OpenGL).
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Adobe AIR supports ActionScript, in addition to some extended contents, such as the Stage3D engine Adobe has developed.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] The number of APIs (Application programming interfaces) available to ActionScript 3.0 has also risen dramatically.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript code is free form and thus may be created with any amount or style of whitespace that an author desires.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] The basic syntax is derived from ECMAScript.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] The following code, which works in any compliant player, creates a text field at depth 0, at position (0, 0) on the screen (measured in pixels), that is 100 pixels wide and high.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] When writing external ActionScript 2.0 class files the above example could be written in a file named Greeter.as as following.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript 3.0 has a similar syntax to ActionScript 2.0, but a different set of APIs for creating objects.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Minimal ActionScript 3.0 programs may be somewhat larger and more complicated due to the increased separation of the programming language and the Flash integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] ActionScript primarily consists of "fundamental" or "simple" data types that are used to create other data types.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] These data types are very similar to Java data types.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Since ActionScript 3 was a complete rewrite of ActionScript 2, the data types and their inheritances have changed.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] There are additional "complex" data types.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] These are more processor and memory intensive and consist of many "simple" data types.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Unlike some object-oriented languages, ActionScript makes no distinction between primitive types and reference types.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] In ActionScript, all variables are reference types.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] However, objects that belong to the primitive data types, which includes Boolean, Number, int, uint, and String, are immutable.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] So if a variable of a supposedly primitive type, e.g. an integer is passed to a function, altering that variable inside the function will not alter the original variable, as a new int Object is created when inside the function.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] If a variable of another (not primitive) datatype, e.g.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] XML is passed to a function, altering that variable inside the function will alter the original variable as well, as no new XML Object is created.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] A reference in ActionScript is a pointer to an instance of a class.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] A reference stores the memory address of an object – operations against references will follow the value of the reference to the memory address of the object and carry out the operation on that object.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] All objects in ActionScript are accessed through references instead of being accessed directly.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Only references to an object may be removed by using the "delete" keyword.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Removal of actual objects and data is done by the Flash Player garbage collector which checks for any existing references in the Flash memory space.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] If none are found (no other reference is made to the orphaned object), it is removed from memory.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] For this reason, memory management in ActionScript requires careful application development planning.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Like most bytecode file formats, Flash SWF files can be decompiled into their source code and assets (similarly to how Microsoft .NET files can be decompiled).
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Some decompilers are capable of nearly full reconstruction of the original source file, approximate to the actual code that was used during creation (although results vary on a case-by-case basis).
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] In opposition to the decompilers, ActionScript obfuscators have been introduced, which transform code into a form that breaks decompiler output while preserving the functionality and structure of the program.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Higher-quality obfuscators implement lexical transformations such as identifier renaming, control flow transformation, and data abstraction transformation which collectively make it harder for decompilers to generate output likely to be useful to a human.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Less robust obfuscators insert traps for decompilers.
[src:haxe-language/actionscript] Such obfuscators either cause the decompiler software to crash unexpectedly or to generate unintelligible source code.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:haxe-language/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Haxe includes a set of features and a standard library supported across all platforms, including numeric data types, strings, arrays, maps, binary, reflective programming, maths, Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), file system and common file formats.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Haxe also includes platform-specific application programming interfaces (APIs) for each compiler target.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] *Kha*, *OpenFL*, and *Heaps.io* are popular Haxe frameworks that enable creating multi-platform content from one codebase.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Haxe originated with the idea of supporting client-side and server-side programming in one language, and simplifying the communication logic between them.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Code written in Haxe can be compiled into JavaScript, C++, Java, Java virtual machine (JVM), PHP, C#, Python, Lua and Node.js.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Haxe can also directly compile SWF, HashLink, and NekoVM bytecode and also runs in interpreted mode.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Haxe supports externs (definition files) that can contain data type information of extant libraries to describe target-specific interaction in a type-safe manner, like C++ header files can describe the structure of existing object files.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] This enables to use the values defined in the files as if they were statically typed Haxe entities.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Beside externs, other solutions exist to access each platform's native abilities.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Many popular IDEs and source code editors have support available for Haxe development.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] No particular development environment or tool set is officially recommended by the Haxe Foundation, although VS Code, IntelliJ IDEA and HaxeDevelop have the most support for Haxe development.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] The core functionalities of syntax highlighting, code completion, refactoring, debugging, etc. are available to various degrees.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Development of Haxe began in October 2005.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] The first alpha version was released on November 14, 2005.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Haxe 1.0 was released in April 2006, with support for Adobe Flash, JavaScript, and NekoVM programs.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Support for PHP was added in 2008, and C++ was added in 2009.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] More platforms such as C# and Java were added with a compiler overhaul in 2012.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Haxe was developed by Nicolas Cannasse and other contributors, and was originally named *haXe* because it was short, simple, and "has an X inside", which the author asserts humorously is needed to make any new technology a success.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Haxe is the successor to the open-source ActionScript 2 compiler MTASC, also built by Nicolas Cannasse and is released under the GNU General Public License version 2 or later.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] The Haxe language can compile into bytecode that can be executed directly by the virtual machines it targets.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] It can compile to source code in C++, JavaScript, PHP, C#, Java, Python, and Lua.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Haxe also has an interpreter called *eval*.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] This same interpreter is also used compile-time to run macros, which allow modification of the abstract syntax tree (AST).
[src:haxe-language/haxe] This strategy of compiling to multiple source code languages is inspired by the write once, run anywhere paradigm.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] It also allows the programmer to choose the best platform for the job.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] Typical Haxe programs run identically on all platforms, but developers can specify platform-specific code and use conditional compilation to prevent it from compiling on other platforms.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] The Haxe compiler is an optimizing compiler, and uses field and function inlining, tail recursion elimination, constant folding, loop unrolling and dead code elimination (DCE) to optimize the run-time performance of compiled programs.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] The Haxe compiler offers opt-in null-safety, it checks compile-time for nullable values.
[src:haxe-language/haxe] The run-time performance of Haxe programs is at comparable speed to handwritten sources.
[src:haxe-language/nekovm] Neko has a compiler and a virtual machine (VM) with garbage collection.
[src:haxe-language/nekovm] The compiler converts a source .neko file into a bytecode .n file that can be executed with the VM.
[src:haxe-language/nekovm] Since Neko is dynamically typed with no fixed classes, a developer only needs to find the proper runtime mapping (in contrast to data type mapping) so that code executes correctly.
[src:haxe-language/nekovm] As the Neko FAQ puts it: "...it is easier to write a new or existing language on the NekoVM than it is for the CLR / JVM, since you don’t have to deal with a highlevel type system.
[src:haxe-language/nekovm] Neko requires compiling before executing, like other scripting languages such as Apache Groovy.
[src:haxe-language/nekovm] Since Neko need not be interpreted at runtime, it executes faster.
[src:haxe-language/nekovm] The Haxe language can compile to Neko code, among other targets.
[src:haxe-language/nekovm] The Neko virtual machine is used to execute a Neko bytecode file, the VM also has the option to convert a bytecode file into an executable file (output changes depending on the target operating system).
[src:haxe-language/nekovm] Neko includes Apache server modules mod_neko for Neko language and mod_tora for hosting the NekoVM application server tora.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] A source-to-source translator converts between programming languages that operate at approximately the same level of abstraction, while a traditional compiler translates from a higher level language to a lower level language.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] For example, a source-to-source translator may perform a translation of a program from Python to JavaScript, while a traditional compiler translates from a language like C to assembly or Java to bytecode.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] An automatic parallelizing compiler will frequently take in a high level language program as an input and then transform the code and annotate it with parallel code annotations (e.g., OpenMP) or language constructs (e.g.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Another purpose of source-to-source-compiling is translating legacy code to use the next version of the underlying programming language or an application programming interface (API) that breaks backward compatibility.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Transcompilers may either keep translated code structure as close to the source code as possible to ease development and debugging of the original source code or may change the structure of the original code so much that the translated code does not look like the source code.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Examples include Closure Compiler, CoffeeScript, Dart, Haxe, Opal, TypeScript and Emscripten.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] So called *Assembly language translators* are a class of source-to-source translators converting code from one assembly language into another, including (but not limited to) across different processor families and system platforms.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Intel marketed their 16-bit processor 8086 to be source compatible to the 8080, an 8-bit processor.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] To support this, Intel had an ISIS-II-based translator from 8080 to 8086 source code named CONV86 (also referred to as CONV-86 and CONVERT 86) available to OEM customers since 1978, possibly the earliest program of this kind.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] It supported multiple levels of translation and ran at 2 MHz on an Intel Microprocessor Development System MDS-800 with 8-inch floppy drives.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] According to user reports, it did not work very reliably.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Seattle Computer Products (SCP) offered TRANS86.COM, written by Tim Paterson in 1980 while developing 86-DOS.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Also, performing only a mere transliteration, the brute-force single-pass translator did not carry out any register and jump optimizations.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] The SCP version 1 of TRANS86.COM ran on Z80-based systems.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Once 86-DOS was running, Paterson, in a self-hosting-inspired approach, utilized TRANS86 to convert itself into a program running under 86-DOS.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Numbered version 2, this was named TRANS.COM instead.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Later in 1982, the translator was apparently also available from Microsoft.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Also named TRANS86, Sorcim offered an 8080 to 8086 translator as well since December 1980.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Like SCP's program it was designed to port CP/M-80 application code (in ASM, MAC, RMAC or ACT80 assembly format) to MS-DOS (in a format compatible with ACT86).
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] In ACT80 format it also supported a few Z80 mnemonics.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] The translation occurred on an instruction-by-instruction basis with some optimization applied to conditional jumps.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] The program ran under CP/M-80, MP/M-80 and Cromemco DOS with a minimum of 24 KB of RAM, and had no restrictions on the source file size.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Much more sophisticated and the first to introduce optimizing compiler technologies into the source translation process was Digital Research's XLT86 1.0 in September 1981.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] The program was written by Gary Kildall and translated .ASM source code for the Intel 8080 processor (in a format compatible with ASM, MAC or RMAC assemblers) into .A86 source code for the 8086 (compatible with ASM86).
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] XLT86.COM itself was written in PL/I-80 for CP/M-80 platforms.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] The program occupied 30 KB of RAM for itself plus additional memory for the program graph.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] On a 64 KB memory system, the maximum source file size supported was about 6 KB, so that larger files had to be broken down accordingly before translation.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Alternatively, XLT86 was also available for DEC VAX/VMS.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Although XLT86's input and output worked on source-code level, the translator's in-memory representation of the program and the applied code optimizing technologies set the foundation to binary recompilation.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] 2500 AD Software offered an 8080 to 8086 source-code translator as part of their XASM suite for CP/M-80 machines with Z80 as well as for Zilog ZEUS and Olivetti PCOS systems.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Since 1979, Zilog offered a Z80 to Z8000 translator as part of their PDS 8000 development system.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Advanced Micro Computers (AMC) and 2500 AD Software offered Z80 to Z8000 translators as well.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] The latter was named TRANS and was available for Z80 CP/M, CP/M-86, MS-DOS and PCOS.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] The Z88DK development kit provides a Z80 to i486 source code translator targeting nasm named "to86.awk", written in 2008 by Stefano Bodrato.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] It is in turn based on an 8080 to Z80 converter written in 2003 by Douglas Beattie, Jr., named "toz80.awk".
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] In 2021, Brian Callahan wrote an 8080 CP/M 2.2 to MS-DOS source code translator targeting nasm named 8088ify.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] The first implementations of some programming languages started as transcompilers, and the default implementation for some of those languages are still transcompilers.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] In addition to the table below, a CoffeeScript maintainer provides a list of languages that compile to JavaScript.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] When developers want to switch to a different language while retaining most of an existing codebase, it might be better to use a transcompiler compared to rewriting the whole software by hand.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Depending on the quality of the transcompiler, the code may or may not need manual intervention in order to work properly.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] This is different from "transcompiled languages" where the specifications demand that the output source code always works without modification.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] All transcompilers used to port a codebase will expect manual adjustment of the output source code if there is a need to achieve maximum code quality in terms of readability and platform convention.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] A transcompiler pipeline is what results from *recursive transcompiling*.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] By stringing together multiple layers of tech, with a transcompile step between each layer, technology can be repeatedly transformed, effectively creating a distributed language independent specification.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] XSLT is a general-purpose transform tool that can be used between many different technologies, to create such a derivative code pipeline.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] By repeating this process, one can turn A → B → C → D → E → F and then back into A(v2).
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] Some information will be preserved through this pipeline, from A → A(v2), and that information (at an abstract level) demonstrates what each of the components A–F agree on.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] In each of the different versions that the transcompiler pipeline produces, that information is preserved.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] It might take on many different shapes and sizes, but by the time it comes back to A (v2), having been transcompiled six times in the pipeline above, the information returns to its original state.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] This information which survives the transform through each format, from A–F–A(v2), is (by definition) derivative content or derivative code.
[src:haxe-language/source-to-source-compiler] There are also debugging utilities that map the transcompiled source code back to the original code; for example, JavaScript source maps allow mapping of the JavaScript code executed by a web browser back to the original source in a transcompiled-to-JavaScript language.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In type theory, **type inference** (sometimes called **type reconstruction**) is the automatic detection of the type of an expression.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] These include programming languages and mathematical type systems, but also natural languages in some branches of computer science and linguistics.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In a typed language, a term's type determines the ways it can and cannot be used in that language.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] At best it might be metaphor; bending type rules is a feature of poetic language.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] A term's type can also affect the interpretation of operations involving that term.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] For instance, "a song" is of composable type, so we interpret it as the thing created in the phrase "write a song".
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] On the other hand, "a friend" is of recipient type, so we interpret it as the addressee in the phrase "write a friend".
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In normal language, we would be surprised if "write a song" meant addressing a letter to a song or "write a friend" meant drafting a friend on paper.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Terms with different types can even refer to materially the same thing.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] For example, we would interpret "to hang up the clothes line" as putting it into use, but "to hang up the leash" as putting it away, even though, in context, both "clothes line" and "leash" might refer the same rope, just at different times.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Typings are often used to prevent an object from being considered too generally.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] For instance, if the type system treats all numbers as the same, then a programmer who accidentally writes code where `4` is supposed to mean "4 seconds" but is interpreted as "4 meters" would have no warning of their mistake until it caused problems at runtime.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] By incorporating units into the type system, these mistakes can be detected much earlier.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] As another example, Russell's paradox arises when anything can be a set element and any predicate can define a set, but more careful typing gives several ways to resolve the paradox.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In fact, Russell's paradox sparked early versions of type theory.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Especially in programming languages, there may not be much shared background knowledge available to the computer.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In manifestly typed languages, this means that most types have to be declared explicitly.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Type inference aims to alleviate this burden, freeing the author from declaring types that the computer should be able to deduce from context.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In a typing, an expression E is opposed to a type T, formally written as E : T.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Usually a typing only makes sense within some context, which is omitted here.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] If there is a way to derive a type for E, then we have accomplished *type inference*.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Given only a type, is there any expression for it or does the type have no values?
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] For the simply typed lambda calculus, all three questions are decidable.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The situation is not as comfortable when more expressive types are allowed.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Types are a feature present in some strongly statically typed languages.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] It is often characteristic of functional programming languages in general.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The majority of them use a simple form of type inference; the Hindley–Milner type system can provide more complete type inference.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The ability to infer types automatically makes many programming tasks easier, leaving the programmer free to omit type annotations while still permitting type checking.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In some programming languages, all values have a data type explicitly declared at compile time, limiting the values a particular expression can take on at run-time.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Increasingly, just-in-time compilation blurs the distinction between run time and compile time.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] However, historically, if the type of a value is known only at run-time, these languages are dynamically typed.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In other languages, the type of an expression is known only at compile time; these languages are statically typed.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In most statically typed languages, the input and output types of functions and local variables ordinarily must be explicitly provided by type annotations.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The signature of this function definition, `int increment(int x)`, declares that `increment()` is a function that takes one argument, an integer, and returns an integer.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] `int result;` declares that the local variable `result` is an integer.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] This is identical to how code is written in the language Dart, except that it is subject to some added constraints as described below.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] It would be possible to *infer* the types of all the variables at compile time.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In the example above, the compiler would infer that `result` and `x` have type integer since the constant `1` is type integer, and hence that `increment()` is a function `int -> int`.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The variable `result2` isn't used in a legal manner, so it wouldn't have a type.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In the imaginary language in which the last example is written, the compiler would assume that, in the absence of information to the contrary, `+` takes two integers and returns one integer.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] (This is how it works in, for example, OCaml.) From this, the type inferencer can infer that the type of `x + 1` is an integer, which means `result` is an integer and thus the return value of `add_one` is an integer.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Similarly, since `+` requires both of its arguments be of the same type, `x` must be an integer, and thus, `add_one` accepts one integer as an argument.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] However, in the subsequent line, `result2` is calculated by adding a decimal `1.0` with floating-point arithmetic, causing a conflict in the use of `x` for both integer and floating-point expressions.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The correct type-inference algorithm for such a situation has been known since 1958 and has been known to be correct since 1982.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] It revisits the prior inferences and uses the most general type from the outset: in this case floating-point.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] This can however have detrimental implications, for instance using a floating-point from the outset can introduce precision issues that would have not been there with an integer type.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Frequently, however, degenerate type-inference algorithms are used that cannot backtrack and instead generate an error message in such a situation.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] This behavior may be preferable as type inference may not always be neutral algorithmically, as illustrated by the prior floating-point precision issue.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] An algorithm of intermediate generality implicitly declares `result2` as a floating-point variable, and the addition implicitly converts `x` to a floating point.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] This can be correct if the calling contexts never supply a floating point argument.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Such a situation shows the difference between *type inference*, which does not involve type conversion, and implicit type conversion, which forces data to a different data type, often without restrictions.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Finally, a significant downside of complex type-inference algorithm is that the resulting type inference resolution is not going to be obvious to humans (notably because of the backtracking), which can be detrimental as code is primarily intended to be comprehensible to humans.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The recent emergence of just-in-time compilation allows for hybrid approaches where the type of arguments supplied by the various calling context is known at compile time, and can generate a large number of compiled versions of the same function.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Each compiled version can then be optimized for a different set of types.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] A version that accepts an integer input and uses implicit type conversion.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] A version that accepts a floating-point number as input and uses floating point instructions throughout.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Type inference is the ability to automatically deduce, either partially or fully, the type of an expression at compile time.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The compiler is often able to infer the type of a variable or the type signature of a function, without explicit type annotations having been given.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In many cases, it is possible to omit type annotations from a program completely if the type inference system is robust enough, or the program or language is simple enough.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] It is through recognition of the eventual reduction of expressions to implicitly typed atomic values that the compiler for a type inferring language is able to compile a program completely without type annotations.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In complex forms of higher-order programming and polymorphism, it is not always possible for the compiler to infer as much, and type annotations are occasionally necessary for disambiguation.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] For instance, type inference with polymorphic recursion is known to be undecidable.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Furthermore, explicit type annotations can be used to optimize code by forcing the compiler to use a more specific (faster/smaller) type than it had inferred.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Some methods for type inference are based on constraint satisfaction or satisfiability modulo theories.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] (Recall that `:` in Haskell denotes cons, structuring a head element and a list tail into a bigger list or destructuring a nonempty list into its head element and its tail.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Type inference on the `map` function proceeds as follows.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] `map` is a function of two arguments, so its type is constrained to be of the form `a -> b -> c`.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In Haskell, the patterns `[]` and `(first:rest)` always match lists, so the second argument must be a list type: `b = [d]` for some type `d`.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Its first argument `f` is applied to the argument `first`, which must have type `d`, corresponding with the type in the list argument, so `f :: d -> e` (`::` means "is of type") for some type `e`.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The return value of `map f`, finally, is a list of whatever `f` produces, so `[e]`.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Putting the parts together leads to `map :: (d -> e) -> [d] -> [e]`.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] It turns out that this is also the most general type, since no further constraints apply.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] As the inferred type of `map` is parametrically polymorphic, the type of the arguments and results of `f` are not inferred, but left as type variables, and so `map` can be applied to functions and lists of various types, as long as the actual types match in each invocation.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The algorithms used by programs like compilers are equivalent to the informally structured reasoning above, but a bit more verbose and methodical.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The exact details depend on the inference algorithm chosen (see the following section for the best-known algorithm), but the example below gives the general idea.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] We also constrain the left and right sides of each equation to unify with each other: `κ ~ [δ]` and `μ ~ ο`.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Then we substitute until no further variables can be eliminated.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The exact order is immaterial; if the code type-checks, any order will lead to the same final form.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] No more substitutions are possible, and relabeling gives us `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`, the same as we found without going into these details.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The algorithm first used to perform type inference is now informally termed the Hindley–Milner algorithm, although the algorithm should properly be attributed to Damas and Milner.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] It is also traditionally called *type reconstruction*.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] If a term is well-typed in accordance with Hindley–Milner typing rules, then the rules generate a principal typing for the term.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The process of discovering this principal typing is the process of "reconstruction".
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] The origin of this algorithm is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Roger Hindley extended this work and proved that their algorithm always inferred the most general type.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In 1978 Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] In 1982 Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] By design, type inference will infer the most general type appropriate.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] However, many languages, especially older programming languages, have slightly unsound type systems, where using a more general types may not always be algorithmically neutral.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms have been used to analyze natural languages as well as programming languages.
[src:haxe-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms are also used in some grammar induction and constraint-based grammar systems for natural languages.
